A brief history of Johnson & Johnson

The story of Johnson & Johnson begins in 1886 when three brothers, Robert Wood Johnson, James Wood Johnson, and Edward Mead Johnson, decided to establish a company that would revolutionize healthcare. The brothers believed there was a need for scientifically formulated products to improve individuals’ health and well-being.

At that time, the pharmaceutical industry was largely unregulated, and numerous health risks were associated with the use of medicines and medical devices. The Johnson brothers sought to change this by creating safe and effective products.

Their first major breakthrough came in 1888 with the launch of Johnson’s Baby Powder. This talcum powder was specifically formulated to be gentle and mild, making it ideal for the delicate skin of babies. Johnson’s Baby Powder quickly became a staple in homes across America and laid the foundation for Johnson & Johnson’s success.

In the early 1900s, Johnson & Johnson expanded its product portfolio by introducing other innovative healthcare products. One key milestone was the creation of the first commercial sterile surgical dressings in 1887. This development revolutionized the field of surgery and made procedures safer and more effective.

Over the years, Johnson & Johnson continued to grow and diversify its business. The company expanded its presence globally and established a strong reputation for quality and reliability. It introduced a range of new products, including Band-Aid adhesive bandages, Listerine mouthwash, and Tylenol pain relief medication.

However, Johnson & Johnson faced its share of challenges along the way. In 1982, the company faced a major crisis when several individuals died after consuming cyanide-laced Tylenol capsules. This incident prompted Johnson & Johnson to initiate a nationwide product recall and implement stringent safety measures. The company’s swift and transparent response not only helped restore confidence in Tylenol, but also set new standards for crisis management in the industry.

Despite this setback, Johnson & Johnson rebounded and continued to innovate. The company expanded into new areas of healthcare, including medical devices and diagnostics. It acquired several companies to enhance its capabilities and broaden its product offerings.

Today, Johnson & Johnson is a global leader in the healthcare industry, operating in three main segments: pharmaceutical, medical devices, and consumer health. The company’s portfolio includes well-known brands such as Neutrogena, Aveeno, Acuvue, and Ethicon.

Throughout its history, Johnson & Johnson has remained committed to its founding principles of putting the needs of patients and customers first. The company’s business model revolves around innovation, quality, and ethical conduct. Johnson & Johnson continues to invest in research and development to bring new and improved healthcare solutions to the market.

Who Owns Johnson & Johnson

As of November 5, 2023, the ownership of Johnson & Johnson is primarily in the hands of institutional investors, who collectively control a significant majority of the company’s outstanding shares. They hold majority ownership of JNJ through the 76.12% of the outstanding shares that they control.

The top 10 institutional shareholders in the company include:

The Vanguard Group, Inc.: One of the largest investment management companies in the world, The Vanguard Group manages a wide range of mutual funds and ETFs. With a stake of 9.84% in JNJ, they own approximately 236,918,354 shares, making them the largest institutional owner;

SSgA Funds Management, Inc.: SSgA Funds Management is a subsidiary of State Street Corporation and provides investment management services. They own a 5.89% stake in JNJ, equivalent to around 141,833,756 shares. They are the second-largest shareholder in the company;

BlackRock Fund Advisors – BlackRock Fund Advisors is a subsidiary of BlackRock, Inc., a global investment management corporation. With a 5.35% stake in JNJ, they own approximately 128,702,928 shares;

Geode Capital Management LLC: This investment management firm focuses on providing services to institutional investors. They hold a 2.06% stake in JNJ, equivalent to around 49,697,798 shares;

State Farm Investment Management: State Farm Investment Management is the investment arm of State Farm, a well-known insurance company. They hold a 1.32% stake in JNJ, owning roughly 31,675,492 shares;

Northern Trust Investments, Inc.: Holding a 1.17% stake, Northern Trust Investments owns around 28,048,637 shares, valued at $4,368,575,213. They have recently decreased their ownership by selling 1,994,993 shares, resulting in a significant 6.64% decrease;

Capital Research & Management Co.: Capital Research & Management is a subsidiary of Capital Group Companies, a global investment management firm. They hold a 1.16% stake in JNJ, equivalent to approximately 27,825,795 shares;

Norges Bank Investment Management: Norges Bank Investment Management is the investment arm of Norway’s central bank. With a 1.08% stake in JNJ, they own around 26,093,398 shares;

T. Rowe Price Associates, Inc.: This global investment management firm offers a wide range of mutual funds and investment solutions. They hold a 1.01% stake in JNJ, owning approximately 24,299,765 shares;

Wellington Management Co. LLP: Wellington Management is a global investment management firm that provides services to institutional clients. They hold a 0.95% stake in JNJ, equivalent to around 22,955,840 shares.

The top 5 mutual funds holding Johnson & Johnson shares are as follows:

Vanguard Total Stock Market ETF: Vanguard Total Stock Market ETF is an exchange-traded fund managed by The Vanguard Group. With a 3.12% stake in JNJ, they own approximately 75,030,233 shares;

Vanguard 500 Index Fund: This is an index fund managed by The Vanguard Group that seeks to track the performance of the S&P 500 Index. They hold a 2.40% stake in JNJ, owning roughly 57,874,177 shares;

Fidelity 500 Index Fund: The Fidelity 500 Index Fund is an index fund managed by Fidelity Investments that aims to mirror the performance of the S&P 500 Index. They hold a 1.15% stake in JNJ, owning about 27,659,440 shares;

SPDR S&P 500 ETF Trust: This is an exchange-traded fund that tracks the performance of the S&P 500 Index. With a 1.11% stake in JNJ, they own approximately 26,693,332 shares;

Government Pension Fund – Global: Government Pension Fund – Global is a sovereign wealth fund managed by Norges Bank Investment Management. They hold a 1.06% stake in JNJ, owning around 25,465,241 shares.

Johnson & Johnson Mission Statement

Johnson & Johnson’s mission statement is “to keep people well at every age and every stage of life.”

How Johnson & Johnson works

Johnson & Johnson’s business model is based on its commitment to improving the health and well-being of people worldwide through innovation and strategic acquisitions. The company focuses on developing and commercializing products and solutions that address the needs of patients, healthcare professionals, and consumers.

Johnson & Johnson develops and markets a wide range of prescription drugs to treat various diseases and medical conditions in the pharmaceutical segment. The company invests heavily in research and development to discover new therapies and improve existing treatments. Johnson & Johnson also seeks strategic partnerships and collaborations to further advance its pipeline and expand its portfolio of pharmaceutical products.

The medical devices segment of Johnson & Johnson focuses on developing and manufacturing a broad range of medical devices, including surgical instruments, orthopedic implants, cardiovascular and diabetes care products, and diagnostic equipment.

The company’s medical devices are designed to improve patient outcomes, enhance surgical precision, and simplify healthcare procedures. Johnson & Johnson works closely with healthcare professionals to understand their needs and develop innovative solutions that address their challenges.

In the consumer health products segment, Johnson & Johnson offers a variety of over-the-counter medicines, skincare products, baby care products, and oral care products. The company’s consumer health brands are well-known and trusted globally, providing consumers with safe and effective solutions for their everyday healthcare needs.

Johnson & Johnson invests in research and development to continuously innovate and improve its consumer health products, ensuring they meet consumers’ evolving needs and preferences.

To ensure the success of its business model, Johnson & Johnson adopts a customer-centric approach and focuses on delivering value to its stakeholders. The company emphasizes ethical business practices, product quality and safety, and a sustainability commitment.

How Johnson & Johnson makes money

Johnson & Johnson operates a diversified business model with multiple sources of revenue. The following are the main ways through which the company generates its income:

Pharmaceutical Products

Johnson & Johnson is one of the leading pharmaceutical companies globally, and a significant portion of its revenue comes from the sales of prescription drugs and over-the-counter medications. The company develops and markets a wide range of pharmaceutical products, including drugs for cardiovascular diseases, cancer, immunological disorders, infectious diseases, and many others. These products are sold directly to healthcare professionals and consumers, contributing to a major portion of the company’s revenue.

Medical Devices

Johnson & Johnson is also a major player in the medical device industry. It designs, manufactures, and sells a broad range of medical devices, including surgical instruments, orthopedic implants, diabetes care devices, wound care products, and advanced diagnostics equipment. These products are used in hospitals and clinics by healthcare professionals worldwide. The sales of medical devices form a significant portion of the company’s revenue.

Consumer Health Products

Johnson & Johnson offers a wide range of consumer health products, including skincare products, baby care products, oral care products, and over-the-counter drugs. These products are well-known consumer brands available in retail pharmacies, supermarkets, and e-commerce platforms globally. The sales of consumer health products contribute to a significant portion of the company’s revenue.

Licensing and Collaborations

Johnson & Johnson strategically collaborates with other companies and academic institutions to access innovative technologies and therapies. The company gains access to new products and technologies developed by other entities through licensing agreements. The company often collaborates with emerging biotech companies to bring their products to market, providing licensing fees and royalties on sales.

Clinical Research and Development Services

Johnson & Johnson provides clinical research and development services to pharmaceutical and biotech companies. These services include conducting clinical trials, data analysis, regulatory support, and project management. These services generate revenue by leveraging the company’s expertise and infrastructure in the healthcare industry.

